Faith in Free Trade
From Cambridge — — recently I was invited to guest lecture in a globalization course taught by two Harvard colleagues. "I must warn you,"
said one of them in advance: "These students are all strong supporters of globalization."
He had asked the students in the first class to choose between free trade and import restrictions, and over 90% favored the former.
And this was before we had even begun to teach the magical effects of comparative advantage.
We know that in real surveys, asking representative samples — — not Harvard students — — the same question would yield a completely different result.
In the United States, the ratio of trade restriction opponents to supporters is 2:1.
But the answers from Harvard students would not seem particularly surprising.
Because those with higher skills and better education tend to be more supportive of free trade than blue-collar workers.
And perhaps these Harvard students have already anticipated their future (financial) prospects and made their decisions accordingly.
Or perhaps they simply do not understand how trade works.
After all, when I met with them, I deliberately asked the same question in a different form, emphasizing the possible distributional effects of trade.
The consensus in favor of fair trade disappeared completely, even more rapidly than I had anticipated.
At the beginning, I first asked whether they agreed with me conducting a particularly magical experiment.
I selected Nicholas and John as volunteers and told them that I had a way to make the $200 in Nicholas's account disappear — — Poof! — — while adding $300 to John's account, and the great work of social engineering could add an additional $100 value to the class as a whole.
So would they allow me to play this little trick?
The result was that only a small minority firmly agreed, many hesitated, and even more opposed the change.

Clearly, the students could not tolerate this form of large-scale income redistribution, even if the overall economic pie had been made bigger.
I then asked why most of them almost instinctively supported free trade, even though free trade would also lead to a similar — — in fact, even more significant — — redistribution of wealth from losers to winners.
The students looked utterly stunned.
I then said, let's assume that Nicholas and John each started a small competing company.
John worked harder, saved and invested more, and produced better products, so he not only had $300 more than Nicholas but also drove Nicholas's company out of the market, causing him a loss of $200.
So how many students supported this change?
This time, the majority voted in favor — — in fact, only Nicholas disagreed!
I then proposed another assumption directly related to international trade.
What if John drove Nicholas out of the market by importing high-quality products from Germany?
Or by outsourcing business processes to China, where labor rights are not yet fully established?
Or by hiring child labor in Indonesia?
This time, the level of agreement with the change decreased in line with the above options.
Additionally, technological innovation will also place some people in a more disadvantaged position, just like trade. What is your stance on this?
Only a few students were willing to curb technological development.
To most people, it is simply a foolish idea to ban the production of light bulbs in order to protect the jobs of candle makers.
Therefore, the students are not necessarily against redistribution; they just oppose certain specific forms of redistribution.
Like most of us, they care about the fairness of the process.
If we are to judge the results of redistribution, we must know the objective circumstances that produced such results.
We would not be upset about Bill Gates or Warren Buffett's immense wealth, even if some of their opponents have always had a hard time, probably because they and their competitors all operate according to the same basic rules and face very similar opportunities and challenges.
But if Gates and Buffett had become rich not through their own talents and efforts, but through fraud, breaking labor laws, destroying the environment, or exploiting subsidies from foreign governments, our views would be entirely different.
If we cannot tolerate redistribution that is achieved by violating moral standards generally accepted domestically, then on what grounds can we feel at ease with redistribution that involves cross-border transactions?
Similarly, when we expect redistribution effects to eventually lead to equality in the long run, and everyone will ultimately benefit from it, we are likely not to mind the transfer of income.
This is also why we believe that even though technology may bring short-term negative effects to some people, we still want to promote its development.
On the other hand, when trade continuously impacts the same group — — low-educated blue-collar workers — — we become worried about globalization.
But many economists ignore these obvious differences.
They tend to attribute the concerns about globalization to stupid and selfish trade protectionist motives or ignorance, without realizing that the most important issue is actually a moral one.
Because they are unable to recognize that international trade — — of course not always — — can lead to redistribution consequences that we would not accept domestically, these economists are also unable to appropriately participate in public discussions.
And since they are morally indefensible, how can they justify trade so strongly?
When globalization occasionally raises a thorny issue related to the legitimization of redistribution effects, we should not respond carelessly with trade restrictions.
There are many pros and cons to consider, including the possibility that globalization may cause wealth deprivation more severe than that experienced by victims within the United States.
But democratic countries should have a more appropriate discussion and make conscious and more thoughtful decisions accordingly.
And the practice of being overly enamored with globalization simply because it makes the cake bigger will inevitably erode its legitimacy in the long run.
